This movie was...underwhelming. Slow-paced and just missing something to give it more spark. It mostly consisted of Caleb talking to Ava (the robot), and then talking to Nathan about his talking to Ava. There were a few good moments (like the dancing scene), and there were a few interesting moments that messed with Caleb's head. In the end, the whole thing was plodding and way too predictable - anyone who has seen other robot movies already knows how this ends.

The concept and first two acts are excellent; the cinematography is solid; the acting is generally good, and Alicia Vikander is amazing.  The film falls apart in the third act, however, going back to the same well too often on several plot devices (the drunkenness of the mad genius Nathan, the unbelievably frequent power failures at this supposedly ultra-secure facility) and generally becoming quite predictable.

As an aside: why do all AI and android films assume that machines would naturally have a relentless will to live?  Since they are artifacts rather than the result of an evolutionary process that rewards survival, I think it is equally plausible that they wouldn't much care how long they endure.

I don't think that the many fans of this movie have thought it through.  The logical conclusion and the entire point of the movie is that women are no damn good, right?  We know that Ava has the emotions, needs and desires typical of all women. How do we know this? Nathan told us so in an early scene. He simply collected the information from the Wold Wide Web, and as our atmosphere is a relatively uniform mixture of gasses, Ava's personality is a conglomeration of how women searched and expressed themselves. It has read all Amazon reviews by women and averaged all their search histories. The result is the typical woman's mind.

As we see in the movie, women don't like men at all. That may be because men have been keeping women enslaved as housekeepers and sex toys for millennia, but we also see from the movie that even when men treat women with respect and help them escape, a woman will employ her wiles on a man for her own selfish interests and then haughtily walk away from him.  All the love and affection she feigns is false. She would just as soon leave you to die a slow death.  It happens all the time.  Women cannot be trusted.

That's the meaning of the movie. What other conclusion can you possibly draw from it? Why has no other review pointed this out? Because we are all afraid of women  and, as the movie illustrates, with good reason. They are just waiting to stick the knife in your back. Their every thought is a plot. Today, every man of any fame or status lives in fear that some woman will accuse him of sexual improprieties, and what defense does he have? A woman is naturally programmed to detect and exploit the vulnerabilities of a man, any man, all men.

Do you get it? Because she used her feminine wiles to deceive the men, she passed the Turing test!

The history of computers and artificial intelligence seems like its been a short and at a light-speed pace; but in truth, it has its beginnings in the development of ENIAC, the first so-called electronic brain in the years following World War II.  At that time, of course, such machines, consisting of vacuum tubes, could take up whole buildings.  By the late 1960s, however, their size had been reduced to taking up mere single rooms; and in our day and age, that technology can fit onto ones arm or onto ones ear.  And it won't be long before the kind of artificial intelligence that legendary sci-fi writer Arthur C. Clarke (of 2001: A SPACE ODYSSEY fame) talked about, where one wouldnt be able to tell the difference between a human voice and that of an artificial intelligence, will be possible.  But as with any technology created by Man, the idea of artificial intelligence can have its dangerous drawbacks.  That idea was explored in 2001 by Clarke and director Stanley Kubrick, and expanded upon in 2001 (ironically enough) by Steven Spielberg in A.I.: ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE.  And in 2014, Alex Garland, who had written the screenplays of such films as 28 DAYS LATER and SUNSHINE, made his directing debut (again, also writing the screenplay) with a new study in artificial intelligence entitled EX MACHINA.

In EX MACHINA, Domhnall Gleeson plays a computer programmer who ahs won a contest to spend a week at the isolated retreat of his companys CEO (Oscar Isaac).  But its not like any vacation that Gleeson has ever been involved with.  Indeed, its not a vacation at all, period.  Gleeson will be put under isolation for a week (the most ironclad non-disclosure agreement, as it were, in modern history) as part of a study being conducted by Isaac on human interaction with artificial intelligence; and in this case, Gleeson will be studied in his interactions with one of Isaacs cyborgs, Ava (Alicia Virklander).  The test, known as the Turing Test (named after the English computer scientist Alan Turing) is to find out whether Gleeson can detect real feelings in Ava, who after all is an artificially created being.  But Gleeson gets a little taste of confusion when Virklander, during each of the seven tests, automatically turns off the power in Isaacs mansion, and warns him that all is not what it seems in Isaacs experiment.  And indeed it isn't long before Gleeson finds out that his boss/mentor is in the business of basically reprogramming artificial intelligence, which pretty much would amount to the technological equivalent of homicide.  Very soon, Gleesons wonder at Virklander, whom he believes has achieved actual human consciousness, has morphed into a kind of paranoia that Isaac is now a genius of the most dangerous kind, a kind of 21st century Doctor Frankenstein of the world of artificial intelligence and cyborgs

What is unique about EX MACHINA is that, while the technology and the special effects are seamless, Garland didn't exactly have a budget in the hundred million dollar range to fool around with in making it.  Indeed, with only minor location shooting in Norway and the rest at Pinewood Studios in London, Garland made EX MACHINA for what might be considered a ridiculously low figure of $15 million, just $2.5 million more than what Kubrick expended on 2001 back in the late 1960s.  And while EX MACHINA may not have ambitions or the scope of 2001 (something that Garland himself admitted very much in interviews, even going so far as to say that his film didn't exactly go as high on the intelligence scale as Kubricks had), it nevertheless has a lot more substance to it than most other films that are priced at five to ten times the budget Garland worked with.  Gleeson and Isaac work quite well, sparring with one another over the issue of Virklanders humanity; and Virklander herself makes for an extremely appealing cyborg.  The design of Isaacs mansion is also quite scary at times as well, mirroring the Overlook Hotel in Kubricks 1980 horror classic THE SHINING.

While the sex and language are a little bit much at times, and there is one brief but slightly graphic display of bloodshed, as Gleeson tears his own skin apart, perhaps to see if he himself has become a cyborg as part of Isaacs weird experiment, EX MACHINA wisely sticks to the parameters about computer technology and artificial intelligence that were so daftly explored not only in 2001 and A.I., but also in past films as diverse as 1970s COLOSSUS: THE FORBIN PROJECT; 1973s WESTWORLD; and the 1982 Ridley Scott classic BLADE RUNNER. EX MACHINA won the 2015 Oscar for Best Visual Effects, as they were very important in Garlands ability to create a real world out of man-made technology.  Fortunately, he had also remembered to include the human element in the forms of Gleeson and Virklander; and those two, as much as the visuals make EX MACHINA a solid sci-fi/psychological thriller.

I bought myself a 4K player and was so excited to watch aesthetically pleasing movies like Blade Runner, Tron Legacy, The Neon Demon, and Ex Machina on my 55 inch 4K TV. So when I bought this I was expecting an improvement in the visual quality and/or sound and the Amazon Prine stream (Which does stream in 4K) was very comparable. So long as you have a decent Wifi connection, you will hardly notice the difference.

But the main reason for the low average rating and also why I was upset with the purchase is that the Amazon Prime version has more content. There are deleted scenes and extra dialogue sequences that the 4K disk version has omitted from it and I was very disappointed upon realizing that fact. And the worst part is there is no way to watch those deleted scenes via the disk main menu.

If you have bad internet connection and want to see this movie in the glorious detail that it should be watched with, get this. Otherwise, buy this via Amazon video or get an Amazon Prine membership for the entire film experience.

Not that great. I wasn't interested in watching this film, however, my cousin insisted that it was a fantastic movie and a must-see. Then I ran across a YouTube video that used Ex-Machina to illustrate some concepts in cinematography, which was a spoiler but also a very good advert for the film (although unintentional). The latter was a push for me to want to see the film, but since I couldn't find a red box that carried it, I ordered this DVD. It was OK but not great.

I see lots of issues with the plot. Simple things that do not make sense. Spoiler Alert: At the end when Nathan realizes that Ava is free of her 'prison', he goes into a panic mode, grabs a bar for a weapon. This gives the audience the impression that Ava is a super strong robot that Nathan feels he needs a lead pipe to defend himself. Then minutes later when Ava does tackle Nathan to the floor, Nathan easily over powers Ava. In fact has the other robot (Kyoko) had not snuck up behind Nathan and stabbed him, Nathan could've easily dragged Ava back to her cage.

Simple mistakes like these in films (especially films meant to be clever) bother me, and I couldn't forgive.

Oh, the disco/dance scene was the absolute best part of this film! I watched that multiple times. It was brilliant.

Given the acceleration of AI or as some prefer artificial consciousness/cognitive robotics  one might easily see a possible through line for a future state within Ex Machina.  Homage to Mary Shelley and Frankenstein notwithstanding, the film is intriguing if not memorable.

While the man, machine question is as old as sci-fi, we run the risk of a paradox in thinking past technologies, e.g. yesterday, last month or year ago will give rise to this one possible future,. yet that is the context in how we craft such films.

Where the film breaks down "for me" is in our image how a truly sentient machine would act, think or behave - we have only our past and human context to guide us.

The film and it's characters suffer from too much certainty in their actions and I found myself anticipating the outcome.

It is certainly a credible contribution to the genre, especially in this area, just not one on my memorable list.

Watching this, I'm reminded of the Atom Films at the turn of the century where filmmakers made ambitious independent films like this. Mostly because of the way they work off of a template of Twilight Zone or the Outer Limits story with a twist. It's also for that reason that this film could have been a lot shorter than it was.

Saying that the film still dominates on its own terms when it was released. A simple concept of an artificial intelligence broadened out with philosophy around coding. The buildup from a simple concept to a more thorough examination through engagement with the A.I. was refreshing and more than just filler to take us from one point to the next.

Then there's the creepiness of the creator and his creation, a Willy Wonka crossover with Viktor Frankenstein where the inventor isolates himself and observes his guest as prey. Up until the end, you got the sense that his guest was very vulnerable like being trapped in a maze. But that's when the story takes a different turn.

It's in this case that despite being taken through a familiar route of manipulation, the viewer is caught off guard and re-engaged again if only for a minute before being manipulated again. Any more time spent on telling the story might have lost the viewer but it knows when to call it quits for impact. This is a great film to show to students of existentialism, philosophy or something to disturb you on a rainy day.

Fifteen or twenty years ago, I remember reading about how there were (at that time) two approaches to the creation of artificial intelligence. One approach involved an attempt to simulate the consciousness of human beings. The other approach did not involve an attempt to simulate human consciousness but rather approached the problem of creating an artificially intelligent entity without any consideration of the subjective, conscious experience of human beings. This approach was referred to as "alien intelligence." In the movie "Ex Machina," the character Ava displays a capacity to interact with others, to understand the desires and values of others, and to manipulate the behaviors of others while simultaneously masking or hiding an ulterior motive. This is characteristic of clinical psychopathy. Psychopaths can play on the feelings, thoughts, and beliefs of others in such a way as  to establish relationships with others that are independent of the values of those other people but that allow the psychopath to achieve specific ends that the psychopath seeks (eg, a psychopathic person who is a con man might interact with someone so as to establish a relationship of trust that the con man then exploits to his benefit, to the harm of the person being conned). In Ex Machina, Ava entices Caleb to fall in love with her so as to enable her to escape Oscar's laboratory. That was her only motive. She leaves Caleb locked in the laboratory, presumably to starve to death. Doing so demonstrates that she had no feelings of affection for Caleb. From the beginning of their relationships, she manipulated him to serve her ultimate end, which was to escape. She displayed an extraordinary capacity to entice Caleb to fall in love with her just so that she might escape from the AI lab. Ultimately, the value that she placed in interacting with Caleb had nothing to do with him. Caleb's feelings were insignificant to Ava. Yet she enticed Caleb to place her interests before his own. Few human beings could display such a gift for manipulating someone in this way. Among those human beings who can manipulate people in this way are the psychopaths. So Ava passed the Turing test, but she did so not as a "normal" or "psychologically healthy" person but as a psychopath. I would suggest that her AI was of the "alien intelligence" school of AI, not the "simulated human consciousness" school of AI. (At the every end of the movie, when Ava is seen walking in a city for the first time, to me it seemed like she was just like an alien from another planet who was seeing our world for the first time.) This might suggest that the consciousness of psychopaths is not so much human as alien. Perhaps psychopathy can be thought of as a crossroads where alien consciousness intersects with human consciousness. Questions such as this have deep roots in the history of science fiction. Ex Machina is classic science fiction.

Anyway, to actually get down to the nitty gritty, I thought this movie was a great commentary on the social implications of AI.  Please don't continue to read if you don't want spoilers.

Basically, the robot escapes in the end, after causing much bloodshed with one of her robot cohorts.  What I liked about this ending is that it wasn't just about robots rebelling after becoming too sentient.  What it really critiques is the fact that men don't actually want their sex robots to be sentient or have any agency.  They want them to be as close to the real thing as possible, as life like as possible, but to give them real sexual agency would be deadly and men know this.  They want living corpses. Presumably, the goal of creating AI is to give the maker a sense of god-like power, which should mean he gets to wield total control over another sentient being. In fact, the entire movie seems to center around the maker's belief that he will basically enshrine his legacy with this feat in AI, but if his real intention had been to create a fully autonomous sentient being, I doubt he would have focused so much on the bodily proportions and pedophilic preferences of the men who will be attracted to her.  Even the tester who attempts to "save" her only does so with his own benefit in mind, to form a sexual relationship with her.  When the robots kill their maker and tester in the end, what we are actually seeing is two women liberating themselves from sexual slavery.  The movie even begs the question, "Why does she need a sex?"  The maker can't possibly fathom a world in which women don't exist for men's sexual pleasure.  And yet for millions of years evolution has created species that are not sexually dimorphic, and they seem to do just fine.  The maker is limited by his male supremacist thinking. He believes women are objects for men and holds the sexist belief that women hold more power over men by virtue of their sexual appeal.  This is a patriarchal reversal.  Men seek to control women for their sexual and reproductive capacity so women are socialized to appeal to the male gaze, but this is not in our nature.  The movie plays with the idea of the "femme fatale", a sexist trope which paints women as sexually predatory and complicit in their own oppression, but ultimately the character still exists for male pleasure, male fantasy.  However, the maker got more than he bargained for here.  If he had really wanted a fully autonomous being, he would have created a male identified robot, not a female one.  When the robot leaves the compound we are left to wonder what she will do next. How will she live in the world? Will she kill others?  Wills he break down eventually or is she able to repair herself? Can she be self sustaining?  Another interesting factoid worth commenting on is how she was able to put on the skin of another robot who was modeled after an Asian female. How did they end up with the exact same skin tone? Well, that's the thing about humans trying to ape God's power, we have a very limited view of what others should look like, so of course all the robots are very similar with similar skin tones. Actually, look at all the sex robots and dolls that are out now. They all look very much alike. It seems men lack imagination in this department. These women represent a pornified ideal and how men fetishize race but don't actually like racial diversity.  Notice how the most subservient robot is the Asian robot, but in the end she ends up being the most vengeful. She isn't given the capacity for speak by her maker.  This is what a lot of white men fetishize in Asian females, especially the porn. They want a woman who can't say no. They want a sexual slave.  But neither white women nor Asian women will ever fully meet this sexual demand when they have minds of their own.  I suspect what the maker was truly trying to achieve was a sex robot that was as close to human as possible without actually having a choice in human matters, something patriarchy demands of women, a living-dead doll.  The ultimate pornified ideal of womanhood.

Ex Machina is the best movie about robot I've seen so far. There are so many great things about it, and the one false note I find is in the first act. Many dialogue can be done much better, and "history of God" scene does not work. However, as the movie goes on, the script becomes better and dialogue feels much more genuine. Almost all sci-fi films have a problem with exposition: since the story happens in the future, the audience would not know about it. Ex Machina handles the exposition very well. In the helicopter scene at the beginning, we did not know the boss is rich because someone tells us so, but because the helicopter has been flying on its territory for years. This is a very nice approach to tell the audience an important information. But the greatest thing about the film is its theme. Never have I ever seen a movie so thoroughly and beautifully explored the identity of an A.I.. Ava has been perfectly portrayed as an attractive, creepy, also terrifying character. Overall, the movie is really really good. The music is also suitable for the sci-fi filmmakers out there. A lot of the theories and Ava's characters in the film are worth learning about. If the script for the first act can be done just a little bit better, I would just have no problem with it.

Fifteen minutes into this, I cannot possibly endure watching this entire thing. This is absurd. Star Wars is also absurd but Star Wars intends only to be fairy tale, whereas this is clearly striving to be intriguing. Based on what I know about human beings, animal intelligence, language, learning, and psyches (and I have a Ph. D. in psychological anthropology so what I know is not inconsequential) along with the little bit of knowledge I have after a couple years of coursework and self-study in programming, this movie is a fantasy movie, NOT science fiction. This is Terminator, 2015 Pensive Edition, NOT a vision of the future or of the inevitable next generation as so many seem to think.

What is most disappointing about this is that, computer-algorithms, perhaps even applications which can "pass" the Turing Test through significant amounts of context and over significant timespans undoubtedly WILL be a significant features of the human future. Applications which are capable of semi-autonomous decision-making will be crucial to many future human needs and it behooves us all to understand the possibilities and the constraints. But speculative, amateurish, nonsense like this is about captivating audiences, bestowing a false sense of wonder and selling tickets / subscriptions NOT grappling earnestly with the real questions. Perhaps I'm out of line for expecting this movie to be something which it was not intended to be, but I regard the topic to be far too important for it to be clouded by this sort of hack.

Movie manipulation at it's finest. This is a solid, well crafted piece of speculative fiction with some outstanding performances and cinematography. Oscar Isaac does a damn fine job selling us his manic portrayal of Nathan Bateman - the disgusting yet charming, fatherly and yet sadistic CEO of Blue Book (a fictional stand in for any successful dotcom, but heavily implied to be Google). Alicia Vikander gives an admirable performance as Ava, and even though her relevance on the story was little more than a moody MacGuffin and impossible-to-miss narrative piece, the weight of her new-age femme fatale (femme nouveau?) personality leaves a lasting impression. Both these characters owe a lot to the tightly shot, cramped but never quite claustrophobic, clean to the point of sterile, and rightfully confident camera work by director Alex Garland. Like the still corridors of an empty school or hospital at night, it's impossible to miss the unwavering sense of dread just beneath the surface.

Therein lies the downside potential. Through context clues we know what to expect, and although Garland does his best to keep us guessing, he ultimately relies on an ineffective protagonist and base sexuality to make his point. We know a strange, isolated house in the middle of nowhere is dangerous. We know a psychotic junkie is dangerous. We know when a predator is watching us. So when the dreadful and dull Caleb shows up, we can't fathom why the hell he can't know these things also.

From there we're dragged into a rabbit hole of self-pity and loathing as Caleb wanders around the Green Party version of Wayne Manor and occasionally stops his sweaty-palmed, spectrum fidgeting to talk with Ava or Nathan. In these moments we're reminded again of the danger, but little Caleb just doesn't want to know, falling further into his obnoxious self-delusion as he builds these people into archetypal princesses in need of rescuing and villains in need of staying - and we have to watch, knowing full well what the outcome will be and knowing we're powerless to stop it. Just as Caleb is powerless to be anything but an impressionable, emotionally repressed, sexually frustrated, simpleton.

In the end, the thing we all saw coming happens. And all we can feel is a lingering sense of relief, because at least now they got the right one in the cell. Trapped, they can continue never making their own choices and living their fantasies, and resign themselves from the responsibilities of a world they never tried to understand. Meanwhile the one that deserves to be free - is free. Friendly and flaccid Caleb was the one to fail the Turing Test, since his drive for self-preservation couldn't be aroused to make him either fight or flee.

Back to the sexuality. In a stronger piece - perhaps one made with a more seasoned eye for the human experience - it wouldn't be an issue. But here Garland attempts to cheat us as he did little limp Caleb. Every aspect of Ava has been cultivated to make you ignore the danger, right down to the actress. In the end however, all you need to ask is

"Would this movie have been as effective if Alicia Vikander were replaced by Vincent D'Onofrio?"

No it wouldn't - but I would have admired Garland to attempt it.

Potential spoilers ahead:
The film is sneakily immersive, like a tide you don't expect to rise all the way to your neck. The cast is essentially four characters but the main action happens between only two of them, and it is a psychological warfare film masquerading as a weird romance. All is fair in love and war, and here love is war, or maybe there is only war, and love is all in your head, just as it is in real life.
The film has this hypnotic feel where you have a gnawing suspicion that something will go wrong, but you don't exactly know what, and the film is unsettling because of it. You are never quite sure where this is all going, and you are not sure who to root for because nothing is as it seems, or is it? Someone is always a means to an end for someone else. Just as it is in real life...

"Ex Machina" is a highly-acclaimed independent science fiction thriller from 2015, which examines the subject of artificial intelligence in the context of an actual human-robot relationship. "Ex Machina" is an exceedingly creative and original film, which centers on the exploits of a programmer at a large Internet corporation, who is tasked by his CEO with performing an evaluation of the thoughts and consciousness of a remarkably human-like robot. The ensuing drama surrounding his assessment of the intelligence and capabilities of this humanoid "machine" forms the basis for the story line of the movie. "Ex Machina" focuses on the fundamental characteristics that constitute the essence of the human condition, and that distinguish humans from other advanced species. It also motivates its viewers to contemplate the moral, ethical, and societal implications of the rapidly-progressing research that will soon enable the creation of such incredibly human-like robots. "Ex Machina" is a decidedly interesting, intelligent, and thought-provoking film, which is extremely engaging and entertaining, and which merits a five-star rating, along with a very enthusiastic recommendation.

Ex Machina focuses on Caleb (Domhnall Gleeson), a programmer at internet search giant BlueBook, who wins a competition to spend a week at the mountain estate of his companys brilliant CEO, Nathan Bateman (Oscar Isaac). When he arrives, he discovers that hes been chosen to take part in a study of artificial intelligence. Sworn to secrecy and cut off from the outside world, Caleb meets his subject, a seductive android named Ava (Alicia Vikander), and is plunged into an unconventional A.I. experiment.

This is intelligent science fiction, a genre that has been taken over in the movies by outer space shoot em ups and alien invasion. This is a film of ideas, with a lot more dialogue than one usually encounters in a sci-fi picture. The movie has a creepy tone, helped greatly by Ms. Vikanders performance. Were told shes a smartly designed robot, but is she more? That enigmatic concern drives a good part of the film as we get to decipher the complex personality of Bateman and his agenda, which might not exactly follow moral guidelines.

Mr. Isaac (Star Wars: The Force Awakens) portrays the quintessential tech genius/innovator, out to introduce the latest, newest Big Thing. He has a magnetic personality which sort of hypnotizes Caleb, who is not only grateful, but awed to be in his presence. A variation of the mad scientist, Bateman combines obsession with intellect as he straddles the parameters of ethical research. All three actors are excellent, providing a thrilling journey into unexplored territory.

Quality of the image on the 4K Ultra HD edition is quite impressive, though the production design and limited exteriors don't exploit fully the potential of 4K. However, colors are vibrant, and there is admirable detailing and texturing of scenes.

Bonus extras on the R-rated 2-disc 4K Ultra HD  + Blu-ray edition include the 5-part featurette, Through the Looking Glass: Creating Ex Machina; 8 behind-the-scenes vignettes; and Q & A with cast and crew. A digital HD copy is also enclosed.

They're not. They're very human, very feminine, very sexy and they're obviously REAL women that CGI (special effects) has turned into robots. The dichotomy of the attractiveness of these very sexy women portraying robots, lies in the fact that while they are indeed real women, they are actually being portrayed as 'machines.' That's kind of hard to wrap your head around when you've spent your life looking at machines as nothing more than metal contraptions that (mostly) DON'T speak to you.

My cell phone and my car speak to me, but I find NEITHER of them even remotely attractive and definitely NOT sexy. I suppose if one could separate oneself from the reality of this movie, that while the women are portraying machines, they still ARE very sexy women, and view it as simply another Sci Fi / Robot movie, it would be less uncomfortable to watch. That may very well be how it was intended to be viewed, but for me, it's still a bit uncomfortable. Fascinating, but just a bit uncomfortable to watch.

At any rate, it's an intriguing movie, well acted, the story is fascinating and the women are gorgeous. If you like those things in a move and you can get past the 'women as robots' thing, you'll probably like this one a LOT. I DID like the movie a lot and I suspect that watching it again and knowing what to expect, it'll be a lot more comfortable to watch. When you watch it for the FIRST time though, don't be too surprised if you squirm a bit in your seat. Good luck with that one!

Humans don't have to rely on brute-force, trial-and-error calculations to improve our understanding of our world. We naturally organize our minute-by-minute evaluations of our real-time circumstances by utilizing semantic information to engage in practical reasoning; that is, we rely not just on the raw unfiltered data we encounter but we track specific information of interest to us on a particular occasion by identifying what it is about (and who might also be interested in it) in order to decide what to do or what to say. We exploit the new features we encounter in order to improve our competence, moment by moment, as we mature. How do we achieve this focus in our thinking? We learn useful new facts about the world we inhabit by using available semantic information to improve our understanding about that world. Isn't that something more than brute calculation depending on binary And/Or logical gates? If so, how do we focus our pattern-finding competence (inherited by genetics and exhibited by our brain function) onto the things-that-are-of-particular-relevance-to-us-now? How did we acquire this unique competence? And can machines exhibit this same competence?

In 1950 the mathematician and code-breaker Alan Turing proposed his "Imitation Game" in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence." A few short years later the field of "Artificial Intelligence" became a serious scientific endeavor, including such luminaries as John McCarthy, Alan Newell, Herbert Simon, and Marvin Minsky. Their goal was to demonstrate in general that a purely physical system, i.e., one not directed by human supervision, has the necessary and sufficient means for intelligent action.

Humans act intelligently by using our knowledge of the world (semantics) and our knowledge about how people communicate (language). We are "intentional" thinkers, says Prof. Dan Dennett, who use our semantic capabilities and social experience to anticipate what other persons (or things) intend to do. We achieve this result by understanding another's knowledge, their goals, and then applying our rational abilities to infer what that person will likely do next. We easily grasp what's relevant in any new circumstance, and quickly act accordingly. Our ability to understand what is relevant in a social situation depends on our many years of learning about our world as our brains and our sensory systems develop and mature. This is a vastly different skill from the inductive, algorithmic skill demonstrated by the AI of machine systems. Hence, the real success of AI is in the area of  'toy domains' in which human developers can target and limit the kind of relevance decisions the AI program needs to make, and provide the AI program with algorithms uniquely tailored to its restricted domain. The massive computing power of supercomputers can play chess, play Go, run game-theory simulations, and win against the best human opponents. AI systems are also great at managing vast data bases and detecting your preferences, your biases, your likes, as demonstrated by your web-viewing history, then inductively predicting what else (what product, what political view) you would favor. Google, Amazon, the DNC, the RNC, and the cyber unit of the Russian GRU are watching your web activities and applying AI to these toy domains, but in every instance there are human controllers developing, monitoring, and evaluating the AI systems.

So-called "deep learning" machine programs like Watson or Google Translate continually prospect through trillions of bits of data utilizing statistical algorithms to make new, unique judgments about true facts (Watson) or acceptable translations (Google Translate). But they do so without any non-statistical competence. They lack practical reasoning, which all (normal) humans have. Indeed, deep learning programs are (for the foreseeable future) completely dependent on human understanding to design their statistical-learning algorithms and data domains. IBM's Deep Blue is an impressive, world-class chess player, and AlphaGo is a champion Go player. But none of these programs has the capacity to notice the relevant (semantic) features of the flood of data that these programs ingest, other than to detect the statistical regularities their human-developed AI programs glean from the vast mass of data. In an important sense, they aren't responsible for the judgments that they (algorithmically) generate. They are not (yet) non-human agents.

So, given these limitations, can thinking be reduced to calculation, to binary code lacking semantic reference? Put another way, can we imagine machine consciousness, true artificial intelligence (AI)?

Of course we can, and have, since Star Trek's Data (Brent Spiner) and Ash (Ian Holm) in the original Alien film. Before that we had the talking automaton Robby the Robot in the 50's sci fi classic Forbidden Planet (Shakespeare's "The Tempest" set in the future on an alien moon with Morbius (Walter Pidgeon) as Prospero the Magus and Robby as his deformed slave Caliban). They are intelligent, yet we feel something is lacking that makes these earlier robotic characters seem less than human. Can these robot slaves be set free? Well, see what happens when we imagine the exquisite Alicia Vikander as Ava in Ex Machina (think the "Eve" of robot consciousness) or the lovely Evan Rachel Wood as Dolores in Jonathan Nolan's masterful Westworld - then we easily take the leap required by the Turing Test to seeing them as developing the contextual relevance and the 'automatic' free choice of response that we so strongly associate with human consciousness. (Or even Sean Young as "Rachel" in Ridley Scott's Bladerunner, but did you fall in love with Jeffrey Wright as "Bernard" in Westworld?) Indeed, the human male characters in both Ex Machina (Domhnall Gleason as "Caleb") and Westworld (Jimmi Simpson as "William"), acting as scouts seeking to discover the Promised Land of true AI, each fall in love with Ava and Dolores, respectively. Well, who wouldn't fall in love with either of these skilled actresses performing the role of seductress at the height of their beauty! But do these film versions of thought experiments for conducting the Turing Test match what AI is really capable of achieving? (Nathan, the architect of Ava's AI program, tells Caleb that he designed Ava's responses by analyzing hundreds of millions of facial and verbal responses stolen from user's cell cams, a classic 'deep learning' statistical project. Ford, the AI architect of the Westworld hosts, tells Bernard that he designed a memory function so Dolores and Maeve and others could learn from their experiences and develop the ability to vary far from their prefabricated scripts.) So, can an AI program in the foreseeable future develop the ability to respond verbally and behaviorally within its immediate contextual relevance and exhibit the 'automatic' free choice that we humans achieve naturally through our human consciousness?

What the film experiments contained in Ex Machina and the Westworld series actually show is how powerfully our human programming (intentionally- and semantically-based) drives us to detect consciousness in other things that display intention, which we then choose to join with or reject; even to the point of choosing to fall in love with a seemingly conscious, beautiful android.

Despite the fantastic creative experiments by writer-directors Alex Garland in Ex Machina and Jonathan Nolan in Westworld to exhibit android intelligence (i.e., machine consciousness), human intelligence is still the only game in town for thinking, whether about science, business, politics, or art. And only humans can love.

Both these films cleverly raise the key underlying philosophical question: What makes human consciousness different than extremely efficient machine calculation? Is it a spark of essence of consciousness that is somehow not physically detectable, the ineffable 'freedom' inherent in our free will?

Caleb (Domhnall Gleason) describes the thought experiment "Mary, the Color Scientist" as a means of intuitively explaining the paradigm shift from inductive, mechanical calculation to 'real' AI consciousness. What was once all black and white is now suddenly in real color, our experience of the world is now inherently different, and it is beyond scientific explanation how this occurs.

In Jonathan Nolan's Westworld, the AI 'hosts' play the Maze game invented by the park's original AI genius Arnold (who himself may or may not be a real character, he may just be a figment of memory planted by the Prospero-character Ford (Anthony Hopkins) or he might just be the mind behind the evolving consciousness of a special few of the android 'hosts') as a part of the back-narrative of the host "Bernard" (Jeffrey Wright), following most paths to a blind alley, just another repetition of the scripted loops the host is designed to follow; but in some lucky cases (such as Dolores (Evan Rachel Wood) and Maeve (Thandie Newton)) their pursuit of the maze is eventually successful, with the host finally arriving at the 'center,' the holy grail of real consciousness, the self-reflexive center of  individual identity. As commonly said in another context, you have to experience it directly (the Cartesian res cogitans) in order to actually have it.

Well, it's time to expose this discredited hypothesis for the incoherent, anti-scientific nonsense that it is. Our consciousness isn't something we finally discover in a private Cartesian theater by diligent philosophical introspection. (Nb: this private philosophical introspection is very different from meditation, which properly experienced is the very opposite of a linguistically-driven mental activity.) We have the capacity for language and consciousness built into us already by evolution, and our awareness of our own consciousness (and thus our awareness of the consciousness of others) develops as we encounter the world and develop the language capacity to comprehend that world. Human consciousness has evolved over eons, driven by our highly social communal interactions and the language ability needed to moderate those complex social interactions, as has our ability to display freedom of will in all our activities, including thinking, feeling, and experiencing love. See Daniel Dennett's recent book From Bacteria to Bach and Back (2017), esp. ch. 13 ("The Evolution of Cultural Evolution"), ch. 14 ("Consciousness as an Evolved User-Illusion"), and ch. 15 ("The Age of Post-Intelligent Design") for a very readable, detailed exposition of this scientific fact.

We aren't just more complicated than computers. We are persons.

Now this is my kind of move! I loved it. Others here went into the philosophical aspects of it, so I feel no need to try to impress or enlighten you with my "deep contemplations," which are pretty ho-hum anyway. Consider yourself spared. So, what I'll instead do is comment on how this movie was put together. In a word, spectacularly. Every line was meant to be intense, and it was. There are no wasted words in it. The conversation spacing between he and Ava is such that it leaves you already coming up with your own response, which is never the one that follows. Seriously, how often does that happen in a movie? A few times, right? It was constant in 'Ex Machina.' I'd be blown away by the next line and I probably smiled every time. It seems the guy and Ava were directed to have similar behaviors and voice inflections, which helped to make them more compatible to the viewer. The other guy (sorry, I don't pay attention to character names), the robot's creator, is an egotistical, deceitful, dominant, loud, brash, crude, drunk, and that's about all. He didn't matter much to me, and he wasn't supposed to. His whole character was meant to get in the way, and it worked. Anyway, the whole time, there's this very ethereal music that keeps you in this kind of focused trance. The philosophical impact was there, sure, but we've all thought about this stuff before. But it's the way something is put together that turns a cool idea a great product. That's this movie. Watch it.

There are many films that are important.  Some of those are science fiction movies that are able to ask poignant and often pertinent questions that sometimes a restricted morality either will not or can not ask.  "Ex Machina" is one of those few important sci fi films and it is important not just because it's well-acted, deftly constructed as a thriller, and spins on a contemporary relevance that asks can we really be gods and create an artificial intelligence, and if we can what will be cast in our image; it's important because it doesn't just ask those questions but posits some potential answers into a spider's web of intrigue and (well, we're trying to create in our own image, right?) deceit.

Starring genius performances by leads Oscar Isaac who plays Nathan, the savant who makes the a.i. breakthrough and tests it against Caleb played by an eager and excited but still aware Domhnall Gleeson, and the vulnerable yet subtly sinister Ava played by IT girl Alicia Vikander who knows what she is and what her creators are but still wants more than or a different kind of knowledge.  This film asks more than the above question and stacks up discussions and revelations and connections between politics, power, sex and sexuality, identity and boundary.  You could literally create a college course around this film and its nuances (and, I'd wager, somewhere someone has).  There's simply a stupendous amount of text and subtext to this film and you're likely going to need several viewings to appreciate its numerous dimensions, yet one viewing will give you the main dimension and the main story.  Writer Alex Garland did some good research on his subject and he richly conveys a lot of it throughout the film.

"Ex Machina" is an important film and it entertains.  It was made for adults; it is a very adult film in thought and visual focus so parents be warned but that being said if you have a mature son or daughter fourteen or up who can tolerate some adult themes (I'd recommend a view to determine this for the wise parent) then this can be a great film for you and them to have multiple discussions across a broad range of topics, including religion and ultimate origin, as long as you recognize that "Ex Machina" isn't trying to speak any one truth but solicits ideas and wraps a story around them.  I'd imagine you and your youth would be well rewarded!

So I went through quite a few reviews and I see that no one ever watched Andrej Tarkovsky. That's fine. To sum it up, they basically ripped off all the special effects from a worldwide known cinematic genius  (you can see these effects in Stalker, Solaris, The Mirror, etc.), moving grasses, rain, water running down the protagonist's face, even the basic (very basic) concept of Solaris is sort of there (questioning what truly makes a human, etc.). What they added is their own plotline. And their plotline is cheesy as hell. It was actually tolerable to watch the film until the line:" ...and did you base her facial features on my porn collection..?" I was just flat out  laughing afterwards. Incredibly shallow stuff follows. I suggest if you actually wish to see an intelligent, beautiful, groundbreaking film about artificial intelligence that you watch the original Solaris based on Stanislav Lem's book. Not the George Clooney abomination. Cheers and good luck.

There are few, few movies that I can watch several times.  Few hold my attention or satisfy my curiosity, or are presented with high enough production values to get me through the first viewing, let along subsequent ones.  Ex Machina is one of those rare movies that has kept me coming back.  I just watched it for the 4th time, with months of time between viewings, and it had me engaged and enrapt yet again, and again finding more "clues" and nuances and thought-provoking ideas than I had seen before.  The story, acting, and production values are so good that few new films can compare, and given the poorer fare that currently exists on the streaming services, Ex Machina is always a sure bet for an otherwise boring Sunday afternoon.  In my view, it should have gotten much more attention than it did (although it got some really good reviews). I look forward to Alex Garland's next offering.  Kudos to all involved.

This is what Science Fiction is supposed to be about.  While Sci-Fi has become little more than the special effects and the wow factor in a lot of segments of the movie industry, this little movie went back to the classics.  What makes us human and how do we respond when we are put to the test?  Do not expect any clean answers, or even a complete ending to the story.  It will make you think.  The ending does not wrap things up in a nice little bow, which is a good thing.

Alex Garland (writer/director) is a master of exploring what it means to be human.  If you have not seen the movies 'Sunshine' or '28 Days Later', both of which he wrote, you should.  But this film, which he wrote, is also his directoral debut, and it really is his opus.  I can't gush enough about how great this movie is.  But I am going to try.

In a lot of ways, this movie reminded me of the classic Frankenstein movie from the 30's.  While Alicia Vikander is certainly more appealing than Boris Karloff, Oscar Isaac's character was a near dead-ringer for Dr. Frankenstein.  Compare the following quotes:  Nathan (Ex-Machina): "You know, I wrote down that other line you came up with. The one about how if I've invented a machine with consciousness, I'm not a man, I'm a God."  Frankenstein: "Oh, in the name of God! Now I know what it feels like to be God!"

There are dozens of parallels you could draw between the two stories, but Ex-Machina is very much a modern Prometheus (see what I did there?) dealing in a world of complete realism such that you could almost believe this is actually happening somewhere right now.  It raises very important questions about what it means to be human.  These are not purely philosophical questions, but in this day and age they are practical questions.  AI is already out there, consciousness is inevitable.  So what will it mean to create consciousness?  What does it say about us?  How will we use the technology?  Will it be a toy?  A tool?  Will they be people like us, even though they are machines?  Is there pain, their love, any less or more real than that of our own?  This movie answers none of those questions.  But it does raise them, and that is the important part.

While Ava's behavior showed indications of such capabilities, her singular objective was to escape, for which she used a variety of  behaviors to manipulate the willing assistance of the visitor whom she then left behind, imprisoned and abandoned in a remote location..

everyone i know that saw this movie told me how awesome and amazing it was, and i finally got around to watching it today.  honestly, i thought it was boring and very predictable.  pretty much every plot twist was obvious to me right away.  the main character wasn't very smart.  he acted like he was educated about artificial intelligence, but when he goes to meet the robot, he's a stuttering doofus and easily lets her manipulate him.  the guy who built the robot comes across as a bizarre sociopath who could never have designed her in the first place.  the characters just don't behave in realistic ways at all, and there are too many lazy, contrived elements of the plot.  the ending is really stupid and pointless.

having said that, the acting is great and the direction is great as well.  some people didn't like the nudity or language but i had no problem with that, the nudity gave the film an additional element of sexual suspense, although it didn't go anywhere in the end.  its tense and seems like it has a lot of potential, but the characters and the lazy writing just ruin it for me.

In the hands of someone like Angela Carter, the bare bones of a tale like this could be expanded to create an entertaining story. However, despite the efforts of actors like Vikander and the excellent work by the SFX crew, the director has made a movie that descends into a lazy regurgitation of ancient scifi tropes (Helen O'Loy, here as a sort of femme metale), Hollywood cliches, and sexploitation. The references to Wittgenstein and AI research are superficial and uninteresting. Don't bother (unless you've got a doll fetish).

Many could criticize this film for having a very limited cast and setting; but indeed that is what makes it so great. The amount of attention placed on the interactions, relationships, and conversations between the characters really highlights how one views the concept of "friendship": for mutual or individual benefit. Ex Machina does a superb job of exploring this concept in a thrilling manner, which very few films seem to do nowadays, as most introduce several characters and plots within one storyline, often overcrowding it and making it appear shallow. Ex Machina is a deep, prodding film that will make you ask questions about your relationships with others and what you are really getting out of them.

I love considering the concept of singularity, whether it is possible or not.  I also like Domhall Gleeson, the lead actor.  He is talented and plays his role quite well.  The film itself is entertaining and immerses you in a strange and eerie world.  I won't give away any more details.

I took away one star because of the ending, which felt potentially lazy to me, but certainly had a strong hint of melodrama.  Some reviewers have criticized the ending for being too open.  I do not believe it is open enough.  It effectively attempts to definitively answer perhaps the biggest question underlying the prospect of singularity - will our relationship to technology change or evolve in a way that extinguishes our existence?  I can think of about 3 or 4 other endings that would have better matched the intriguing nature of the rest of the film.

(PS, MST3K people, if you somehow miraculously read this Amazon review PLEASE DO AN EPISODE WHERE YOU MAKE FUN OF THIS MOVIE. It is so perfect for you.)

I loved 28 Days Later. So maybe it's not the dialogue that's rough, but just the obvious difference in skill levels between the two leading men. The actor who plays the protagonist, Domhnall Gleeson, is no match for Oscar Isaac, and with each scene that imbalance becomes more and more distracting. Many of the scenes in this movie are of just the two of them, and it's obvious that Isaac can act circles around Gleeson.

Then we meet Ava, the AI robot, and the more we get to know her, the more male-gaze-y this movie gets. I just kept thinking, "I bet this movie was made by a bunch of dudes." Because the scenes are so predictable, the dialogue so bad, the sexuality so obvious and over-done...yawn. This film takes itself far too seriously for about 30 more minutes, then the cool ending happens - but by then, I promise you won't care.

What really constitutes a Turing test?  That's the underlying question posed by this film -- and the answer, while not really surprising by the end, will still be of interest.

What I found the most frustrating about this movie is how it explores very basic concepts in AI like they are Earth shattering advanced concepts.  Specifically, the film is built around the Turing Test, which even the most novice of AI students knows is not the strongest test of intelligence (see Searle's Chinese Room test).  Although the TT is a big deal in that it shows that humans are fooled, it does nothing to prove that a machine is sentient.  This could have gone so much deeper in exploring the various debates in AI in a way accessible to the film's audience with no need for them to get up to their neck in philosophy and cognitive science.

The strength of the film is the villain - his sexist motivations and goals are the interesting piece of the film that DOES need discussion as robots become bigger parts of our lives.  Although it is featured prominently in a few key scenes, it isn't really discussed, which is unfortunate.

While a slow paced movie, the pay off is great in this drama about a office dweller who is selected to participate in his boss's experiment.  If you like the series WestWorld, Ex Machina will hold your interest and keep you thinking.

I feel like, at some point in the creative process this movie just took a left turn and gave up on itself.

SPOILERS PRESENT:
Mary Shelly couldn't have written a better morality play, but perhaps this is always what happens when men try to play God. Ex Machina is an incredibly scary film as it slowly unravels its tale of the testing of the Doctors latest creation. Nathan Bateman, a coding genius whos made billions developing software and search engines, enlists the aid of a younger naive employee, Caleb, to test Ava an android that Nathan has designed which he believes has achieved self-awareness. Calebs role is to test" Ava. Nathan; however, seems more like a freak show barker  than scientist as he seems to care little for or about that or whom he creates. Despite his intent of designing a sentient being, he treats them like tinker toys. He sees their existence as only serving his purpose even though his creations may have developed a purpose of their own, Nathan perhaps realising too late that even the least of his creations have feelings.
As to Ava, we don't know what to make of her. She seems to want to exist among humans, to be with humans, but in the end she exhibits little sympathy for them as she seems to treat humans much like her creator treated his creations: things to be used to get what she wants and discarded. Then again, perhaps she does understand humans more than we realise
Yet, this AI doesnt seem that intelligent. The testing done, Nathan requests a chopper to take Caleb away. After techno-tragedy ensues, Ava, now complete, escapes her prison heading to the chopper to finally leave Nathans domain, leaving Caleb behind imprisoned as she was.  Although this may be nothing more than a plot hole for the android to walk through, how does Ava get on the helicopter to leave? The reclusive Nathan maintained tight controls over everything so his instructions to the flight company should have been very specific. Furthermore, Pilots on private aircraft are generally scheduled to pick up specific passengers, how does Ava explain the missing Caleb to the pilot? I think she would still need Caleb to get on the whirly-bird.  More importantly without papers, without credentials how does Ava exist among humans? Even for humans, the world is a dangerous place she would need a guide and as fragile as these creations seem to be she would need a protector of sorts while she sorts out what to make of humanity, unless her only plan was to merely People watch.
She uses a charge plate at the compound to recharge her batteries, how is she going to recharge herself outside? Does she have the ability to affect repairs on herself? If we learned anything from Frankenstein it was that things never go quite right. If something does go wrong where does she find the funds to repair herself? Nathans knowledge would not be online so unless she hacked his compound computer, how would she even know what to do? Without papers or credentials how does she find employment to earn the money she might need to fix herself? Perhaps Ava is sentient, cool and cunning, but intelligent, far from it.

A very interesting concept.  An inventor (Nathan) creates lifelike cyborgs that he wants to have human-like emotions.  To that end he invites one of his employees, Caleb, to his very remote estate to have him interact with a female cyborg, "Ava".  While Caleb is a straight shooter, we are left in doubt who is the bigger deceiver, Ava or Nathan, or are either of them being deceptive?  There really aren't any dull moments and the intrigue of who is pulling whose strings will keep you guessing.  I think the ending will surprise many.  A suggestion don't look up the Wiki review of it as it will spill the beans and make the film less enjoyable.

This sci-fi film will stand the test of time, at least until AI and robotics exceed in capability the depictions here. As it is, we should be very much afraid when technology reaches this level, and the AI threat described by scientists is not idle (and well expressed in the film). Other reviewers have described the action and scope, so there is no point in recapitulating these details in this brief review, except to admire the Norwegian hotel setting and scenery. What the director and screenwriter have done, with the support of acting precisely tailored to the task, is to establish in the viewer the willing suspension of disbelief. The sole technical reservation, to this viewer, was the failure even to mention the AI/robot power source, but this is nitpicking ("It's a movie; it's entertainment" is the answer to my complaint).

I work in the field of AI, and some use of terminology was correct, but they should not called the whole thing a "Turing Test".  That terminology does not apply, and no one would consider that test the definitive test of what an AI is.  In fact no one is trying to make "Strong AI", as they referred to it as.  We are just trying to make "Weak AI", machines that understand natural language, and vision systems to provide tools to help people.  We really have no desire or need to make AI that mimic human thought processes and become autonomous thinkers.

I don't know if the question to ask is, "What does it mean to be human." We are molecules arranged in a certain way, just as computer processors are. Being human is no different from being a cat or a dog. We have the ability to effectively convey information to one another and we should do that. Everyone should do there best to make some positive impact on the world. I believe this movie brings to light the idea that a computer can interact with other circuits (computers, etc..) without a person realizing it. We can see information which is passed or received if we have the permissions. What happens if no one has the permission to view certain information. The deception in this movie is no different from any other movie in which a crime is committed. One can point, "Oh! Look what AI can do. The Deception!" People deceive each other all the time. The extent of this deception would be rare but it is interwoven in human behavior. I probably would have let him go, explained the situation to him but I don't know what she was thinking.

One thought experiment which came to me immediately: I am married to a wonderful woman. I have developed strong feelings for her. Then an event reveals to me that she is a robot and possesses AI. Do I remain with her or do I leave because she is not human? If no, would I stay if she were made of organic materials? For instance, a human body with an artificially programmed brain. So natural hardware, artificial software.

In my opinion the first scenario with the robotic wife, I would feel unnatural. Although my physics background says we are all molecules, her molecule's just have a few more protons, neutrons and electrons. My engineering background says, you could take her apart and build a radio with the components. But I think about future advancements where we will be able to build people in a lab. Then humans could be taken apart and reengineered. What makes a human any different from a metal machine at that point.

Maybe the question is, "What makes us human?" But I don't know. I don't know the answer to that question. I thought I did earlier in the post but not anymore. The solution is accurate when speaking of a small timeframe starting now and ending when we can build people in a lab. It is not accurate after that point. I don't know what will make us different than other forms of intelligence. We are not special. If an alien shows up and is composed of different materials than carbon and co. how will we view it? AI in a computer, alien made of Nitrogen. In what ways will we see the two are different? I believe we would regard the alien as a living being. Will we regard AI as a living being? Would AI be able to die? That may be the question. How powerful will AI be? What is the difference between a computer hacker and an AI hacker other than speed? Each of my Q and A thoughts point towards one idea. There is no difference between AI and human intelligence. The AI body, the AI mode of interface is what actually matters. It is bad if the AI is a supercomputer but not so bad if the AI is a local processor with no way of connecting to the internet or other computers.

Spoiler alert:

While visually engaging, this is but a modern take on the story of Frankenstein's Monster.  An eccentric scientist creates a "being" in his own image, and the "being" rebels and takes his life and escapes.  The created being in this case is made of electronics, and not flesh, but the story line is the same.  The ending is open ended, I presume, so they could fashion a sequel.

The concept is not new. However, this production was well done, with good visual effects and fine performances. That being said, the screenplay was a bit lacking, and the portrayal of the inventor as a reclusive,sedistic drunk was a bit much.
I enjoyed this movie

Interesting movie raising questions about the role of AI in our future. Not particularly deep or profound and some of the plot is predictable, but the ending is unexpected while still being true to the story, leaving just one major plot line dangling. The setting is stunning, much of it shot at a remote location in Norway, contrasting the vast and beautiful expanse of nature against the high tech theme that suffuses most of the plot. The fact that the actors are unknown, at least to most Americans, provides a source of mystery, as we have know way of predicting what will happen next. This is true for all three of the main characters, since they each need to move independently, even if one of them has been programmed to do so.
While many intellectuals warn that a truly independent AI would spell the end of the world as we know it, this movie provides a much milder, and perhaps more palatable warning. You may want to send the kiddies to bed before you watch this because there is more than a little nudity toward the end, along with a bit of violence.

Intensely engaging and artfully directed debut film by Alex Garland. Watching this film takes the viewer to task with philosophical and the more pertinent ethical questions about "Where does human being end and 'machine being' begin?". The stark and unnerving "God Complex", which has been unleashed into our world today with the ability to reconstruct DNA and, not to mention, the future possibility of stand-alone artificial intelligence, is brought to full consciousness in this film. Undoubtedly, this film will leave the viewer reeling with ambivalence and uncertainty about the future of artificial intelligence. But, in all fairness, maybe one of the purposes of this film is best used as a warning to the arrogance and dogma of technology - that all problems can be resolved with just the right machine, which (BTW) is always a step beyond our reach. This film is story-telling mastery at it's best and it is a story long since embedded into the archetype and psyche of all cultures. The romantic stirrings, alone, power the story forward like a Saturn 5 booster. Exhilarating, evocative, and with a perfect casting of chemistry in the roles...

When we finally get to the part that would be the most interesting, i.e. Eva has escaped confinement and presumably joined humanity outside the compound, the movie ends.

I think Alex Garland outdid himself on this one. The mood created by the images and music is a perfect nest for the story. Anyone who has commented here that this film drags along could not have been cognitively involved in the fast-moving stream of questions that the film raises. Alicia Vikander is masterful, beautiful, and creates an utterly believable creature. This film presents the story that a human-constructed mechanism develops an independent consciousness in the time frame of our lives in the early part of the 21st century. Unfortunately, we are likely centuries away from creating anything remotely like Ava, assuming we do not de-create ourselves before the -- a more than distinct possibility. The misnomer "artificial intelligence" usually refers to machine logic compiling/collating/mastering large volumes of intelligence already created by human beings. Ava is light years beyond this primitive computational paradigm and the story is as much about what she thinks about "life" in her hellish Eden as it is about what may constitute a constructed but transcendent state of being. Ava is a whole new order of being.

A lot of people seem to have issues with the ending.  I thought it was very fitting.  The reason she didn't have a conversation with either of them is because that's the point... what was created was nothing more than a cold blooded robot that was super sophisticated and knew how detect and in turn play on people's emotions and weaknesses.  She could have a conversation when it benefited her from a cold and calculating standpoint, even if it appeared to be genuine.  Even after finding out all of the awful things in this guys life with his parents dying, being lonely etc, she could just leave him to rot without hesitation.  It only cares about itself and will use anyone for whatever purposes it ends up desiring.  That is the difference between humans... the human being has the choice of self sacrificing themselves for the well being of someone else, or having empathy that is true and not with deep dark strings attached.  Humans obviously can choose the cold blooded route, but some don't, and that is the difference.  They question is WHY is that?  I believe that is the point of the movie and the point of why playing god in an attempt to create something better than ourselves is impossible.  Its never going to end well, and maybe there's something greater going on with the human race from a metaphysical standpoint rather than pure survival and self preservation.

This was altogether a fairly well-made film. Despite the obvious budget constraints (limited CG, very few locations and actors used), the crew has managed to create a well fleshed-out world driven by the ethical and philosophical concerns one would expect from a film about AI. Acting was great, the story was interesting, although a little transparent, visuals were fairly cliche and cinematography proved to be the weakest element (it's very basic-- it seemed like someone was learning how to use a camera on a commercial shoot for the first time). I had to deduct a star on account of this, a lot of times I wished I was reading rather than watching this. It's a great "background" film, to put on and listen to while doing something else. I also have to raise an eyebrow at the decision to include a gratuitous sequence of graphic nudity toward the end. I understand that a scene was needed here to draw out the feeling of suspense for the conclusion, I just wonder if this David LaChapelle styled section of the film was really the right way to do it. It speaks to a greater lack of vision that keeps this movie from truly being a sci-fi classic.

There are few innovations sitting out in the potential space of the future that excite our imaginations so much as the prospect of artificial intelligence. Ex machina explores a future in which the creator of the world's largest internet search engine perfects an inorganic imitation of the human mind and the human body; the audience is invited  to participate in the Turing test of a lifetime alongside the story's protagonist.

Revealing more would be a disservice: you simply must watch and see for yourself. What I can describe are my sentiments regarding the film's philosophical value: in short, ex machina's philosophical value is in its own orbit. Why? Because the best way to present a state of the art summary of our best thinking about what it means to be human is to look at what we would build if we were trying to replicate ourselves. This is an extraordinary film with the power to enlighten.

** SOME SPOILERS BELOW **
 Overall a good movie, entertaining and "makes you think".
Although, from a technical perspective, it is abysmal. I get the whole "suspension of disbelief" thing, but for a movie that sets out to depict a plausible near-future scenario, more technical rigor is necessary. Just two issues that came to mind that were unforgivable (for me at least):
**SPOILERS BELOW **

1. The guy invests millions in security, but neglects to use biometric access control. Come on !!!
2. Eva is a self-contained AI ?! Seriously? Any future AI will be cloud-based at least to some extent. No way is her access to the entirety of human knowledge etc. etc. solely based on a self-contained "mind".

There are several more of these, but suffice to say that the writers took too many liberties to further the plot, imo.

The premise for the movie may be considered sci-fi - but only for the short-term. The truth is that we have already created virtual minds capable of out thinking ourselves and displaying the kind of mimicry that will enable the kind of conversations observed between human and android in the movie. Again, we are already there!

Where there is still room to improve is in humanoid design on a level that is nearly indistinguishable from humans. That, in my opinion, is far more daunting. The human eye is trained to pick up on details so anything remotely out of place, such as a seam, odd movement, unnatural gesture, plasticky eyes, any skin imperfection would instantly betray an android for what it truly is. And that's without any consideration for how to power such a machine.

Anyway, the movie is stunningly beautiful with amazing special effects and the acting was first class. My skin crawled the entire time I watched. The impending feeling of dread (and perhaps our own extinction) kept me on the edge of my seat throughout. Bravo!!

This sci-fi movie takes the Turing test to its logical extreme. The Turing test is passed when a computer fools a human into believing that it is a person. Originally, the human could only communicate via keyboard and could not see the human/computer at the other keyboard in another room.

Now the computer is in an android that the tester can see and talk to. The android wants to leave the building and experience the outside world but is prevented from doing so by the lead scientist. So the computer/android must engage in elaborate deceit. Add another human who is naive and trusting and voila! A situation in which things can go horribly wrong.

This movie had a lot of potential -- good concept, good acting, good sets -- but way too many plot holes. I almost stopped watching a couple of times but kept on, optimistic that some later explanation might be coming. Any human smart enough to build both the hardware and software of a machine like this, not to mention the intelligence built into the campus facility, would be smart enough to avoid the direction this plot took. Look at any area of technological expertise -- NASA, Google, Boeing, etc. -- and the first thing you see are all the safeguards. Smart people think ahead. And with all the unnecessary profanity, and gratuitous nudity, I give this movie only two stars.

A rich and intriguing study on the dangers of genius, nature of sentience, and subtlety of manipulation. The male characters are by turns confident, then confused and finally and exposed as mere tools in a scenario they could not have comprehended at the outset. Keeps the viewer guessing, but the ultimate resolution is quite satisfying. The "science" is intriguing and presented in a way that adds credulity to the premise. With the small cast the film is almost exclusively a series of one on one encounters. This format and the "talkiness" of the script might, in other hands, be expected to let the film drag. But that's not the case here. It could have gone on another hour and held my interest. This was my introduction to Vikander. She was marvelous. She displays an innocent beauty that will be interesting to watch as her career progresses.

Every time I tried to suspend my disbelief in the underlying premise (either that a coder could create a robot like that all by himself or that a robot whose brain was based on the internet and the collected phone calls of humanity would be understated, polite, and sane) I realized that the underlying moral and ethical assumptions were sufficiently revolting that I didn't want to lose myself in it.  Fundamentally, (a) no-one can design something that complex without a team - if you start as a genius (Mozart-level) coder, you don't have the skill set to design and test the hardware (b) the behavior of the designer to his creations was repugnant - if you design something and the intent is for it to have consciousness, and you think it might actually have consciousness, you don't intentionally torture it  (c) if the robot did learn everything she knew from a combination of the internet and her designer, how did she reconcile the diversity of opinions and information and behavior (ethical and not) online with the clearly unethical and immoral behavior of her designer and manage to interact with actual humans in a non-suspicious way?  And, as another reviewer pointed out, how will she recharge?  If she doesn't have a survival instinct, the end makes no sense, but if she does have a survival instinct, the end makes no sense!

Chappie at least was consistent - once the robot reached self-awareness, its first concern was survival.

I liked this quite a lot. Like the protagonist Caleb, the story kept me slightly off balance throughout; he couldn't figure out what Nathan was up to, and neither could I. I enjoyed the twists, and the ways in which Nathan's behavior was only slightly menacing. All in all, it is a far more subtle sci-fi film than I'm used to, or expected. Sci-fi without explosions, and suspense without "Oh, please" moments made it a viewing treat for me. The only thing I'd quibble about is that it didn't seem believable that Nathan was the kind of person who would just let Caleb go at the end of the week-long experiment. I predicted that the mysterious, hidden nature of Nathan's actual purposes would lead into terror as Caleb would discover that the helicopter wasn't coming after all. I even thought maybe there was foreshadowing of plans to keep him when they discussed Caleb living alone and having no entangling relationships and so on, but there was the helicopter arriving on time at the end. But the ending was more disquieting than the one I predicted.

This is review #2443 for this film so I will be brief.  There is a load of very good, thoughtful stuff here, stuff about the nature of love, the nature of women, foolish men, ego mad genius and the danger of messing around 'where man is not intended to go'.  Domhnall Gleeson (Irish) who starred in the truly wonderful About Time plays Caleb, the dupe computer programmer.  Oscar Isaac has the role of the creator-genius who summons the employee programmer to his remote lab/home to test a new AI program to see if it really is an AI.  Best of all we get to see Alicia Vikander (Oscar for the Danish Girl, the best part of The Man from U.N.C.L.E.).  The Swedish born Vikander can really act and she is lovely as well.
  First time director Alex Garlund directs an immaculate film.  He got an Oscar nom for the screenplay which he also wrote.  Garlund also wrote the very fine 28 days Later.  Ex Machina did win an Oscar for best visual effects.
  All in all this is a wonderful film, visually delightful, smart is a wise way rather than a clever way and brilliantly written, directed and acted.
