A  beautiful movie to look at and watch. The production values are of the highest quality. The message that Artificial Intelligence (AI) is coming is not earth-shaking in and of itself. In the beginning of the story, the AI element is innocent and almost seductive. Then, like all new things we experience in life, the full impact of this new element emerges with continued exposure and social interaction. Very quickly the seductive innocence becomes a background facet of the ominous and cold-blooded, potential menace of the widespread, covert  and unconstrained intermingling of AI into human society.

A cerebral piece that, if you stay through the first and second acts, it pays off in the third. It's one of the best robot/A.I. movies I've seen (way better than Chappie as far as plot goes). It seemed to cover most of the pitfalls of creating strong/general A.I. and did so in a subtle, mature and erudite way. If you're looking for a movie night, I would warn you that there's not much action for the first two thirds of the movie.

It can take a lot to get a five star movie review from me. The main reason this one didn't is because it didn't leave an indelible imprint on my soul. That's a pretty high bar for any movie. In every other respect, Ex Machina is nearly perfect. It takes an old concept, that of artificial intelligence, and gives it fresh new perspectives and ideas. The protagonist is easily relatable, and all of the characters are believable (which only makes parts of the movie that much more horrifying). Special effects were (to my admittedly untrained eye) very well executed, as was the writing.

There was one exception that left me feeling like "no, if it had bled that much, he would have needed stitches, it wouldn't have just stopped on its own." This thought did momentarily interrupt my suspension of disbelief. (I am refraining from going into details about the scene in question so as to avoid spoilers.) At any rate, that moment was a mild distraction that I was able to set aside easily enough, because the rest of the movie was so captivating. Even though I'm familiar with many of the tropes of A.I. movies, this story still threw some refreshing curveballs, especially in terms of Caleb's anticipation of Nathan's actions. Caleb turns out to be a bit smarter than he looks, which is a neat trick, given that he never looked dim to begin with.

Potential viewers should be aware that Ex Machina explores themes of sexual exploitation; it does so intelligently and not gratuitously, but those who are triggered by such content - or those who might be watching this movie with young people - would be wise to use caution. It's a well-told and worthwhile story, but it is a mature story.

I have begun to question in recent years if I'm still really "into" the science fiction genre; this movie left no doubt in my mind that I am. It's been many days since I watched Ex Machina, and I'm still thinking about some of the ideas it explores.

There was a lot of negative media about this movie, regarding its supposed misogyny. I finally saw it on Amazon. I think that the hype seized on what was clearly a mistake on the maker's part of displaying more than a little bit of full frontal nudity, and extended their critique to the storyline, where it doesn't belong. In other words, the core story was actually very intriguing, as good sci-fi often should be--if things turned out the way we currently dream, would it actually work out, or would something we never considered sneak in with it, and ruin it? This joins the ranks of robot/AI stories gone wrong in splitting hairs ways, and I thoroughly enjoyed the mind bending. I thought the acting options available to two of the female was great, and the special effects haunting. The problem was clearly that, though the nudity had its place in this particular storyline, it was simply indulgent in its long, drawn-out scene painting. America is still prudish enough as it is, but too many people think they're saying something important by throwing gratuitous nudity into storytelling. Anyway. I enjoyed the movie once. I probably wouldn't watch it many times. Alicia Vikander as Ava was refined and intense. Dohmnall Gleeson and Oscar Isaac were capable in their roles. Sonoya Mizuno was committed and creepy. If they had balanced out the sexuality, I probably would have given it 4 stars. I think what keeps it from bumping up to 5 is that, aside from wanting to be freed, we really don't end up knowing much about the consciousness that was Ava, the AI, in the end. I don't like coming to the end of a story, perhaps shaving rooted for one of the characters, and then come to realize I don't really know her at all. It left me feeling empty, and futile. Its a dark movie, so I understand ending up feeling less than happy, but I think if I had some sense of the persona of Ava at her core, and could have happy or frightening dreams of what she would do out in the world, I would have been more fulfilled by the film.

I've known about this film for quite some time now, and didn't get quite around to watching until I had a lengthy flight.  As I was watching the film, I suddenly recognized the voice of the actress playing the role of the A.I.  As I continue to focus on the voice, a light bulb went off in my head and I realized that it was Alicia Vikander who was playing the role of the A.I.

I've been such a big fan of hers ever since I saw her amazing performance in the Danish Girl.  She definitely shows an impressive range by taking a role that I am sure can be perceived by many other actors as deceptively easy to portray (in regards to playing a robot).

Vikander's performance beautifully brings the character A.V.A. to life by magically bringing the robotic and human emotional elements combined into one to the point where if you listen to her with your eyes closed; you would not be able to tell if what you are hearing is that of artificial intelligence, or human.

Ex Machina presents a sharply feminist critique in its exploration of beholding, identity and ownership within the framework of an AI story.

Beautifully shot and extremely well-acted, the movie also explores questions about machine intelligence as a topic in itself -- truly the one area I wish the film had pushed farther into, even at the risk of alienating potential viewers. This is a smart movie, and its creators would have had nothing to apologize for if they'd pushed it to be even more high-concept.

A few moments did feel slightly contrived, but that complaint encompasses less than a handful of scenes in a nearly seamless, intelligent, and intentionally uncomfortably film.

Without providing any spoilers, I would point out that Ex Machina is framed as a story about two men in a position of (presumed) power and control over a feminine body. Survivors of domestic and sexual abuse who are aware of their own sensitivities in such matters may appreciate the trade off of researching the film's plot a bit further (and missing out on some of the movie's tension and reveals) rather than find themselves underprepared for some of the content.

Isaac's character, Nathan Bateman, is a bit overdone. He is supposed to be a internet search engine billionaire. We should be sophisticated enough to deal with a plot full of anti-heroes, but must the robot maker be a crass tacky simulacrum of current techy billionaires? Did Ava pass the Turing test?  The Turing test as stated in the movie asks the question "is artificial intelligence true intelligence that is possessed by human beings" or is the artificial intelligence only mimicking what has been programmed  to see as true awareness of conscience and thought.
This implies to have true human intelligence there has to be an awareness of emotions of oneself and of other beings.  In the movie, both Nathan and Caleb come to the conclusion that Ava does have true intelligence because she is able invoke  human characteristics such as empathy, sexuality, emotional manipulation and deception in order to orchestrate a plan to ensure her survival and gain the most basic human desire of freedom.  However, the movie allows the viewer to evaluate this conclusion and in my opinion even suggest that the conclusion of Ava passing the Turing test is a fallacy. The interpretation is hinged on our own view of what human intelligence really is.  In the end Ava is shown to have a flaw in her conscience much like psychopaths and narcissists have in their lack of empathy and connection with other's emotions.  However, the difference may depend on whether Ava is aware that she possesses those flaws.  These are profound questions posed in the film.  The film has one shortcoming at least in my opinion in the character development.  It was difficult to have any connection with any of the characters and plot involving Caleb's role was predictable.

This is one of those movies that, while I enjoyed it as a suspensful psychological thriller, I couldn't really get into it as science fiction.  Yes, there were androids and great special effects but that doesn't make a film sci-fi.  In this case the androids could just as easily have been human beings,  Deeply disturbed, psychopathic and sociopathic human beings, but humans nonetheless.

Of course the two actual humans were obviously not playing with a full deck either.  One is manipulative, overbearing, self-destructive, and arrogant while the other is naive' to the point of it being painful to watch.  You'd think living in the future he'd be aware of all of the reasons not to trust robots but yet he insists on playing the part of gullible puppet. Ahh.. I guess a pretty face on a metal alloy transluscent body is just too big of a turn-on to resist.

The story unfolds bit by bit, sometimes a bit too slowly.  Questions pop-up like, how does she know she's a girl? Why didn't the brilliant programmer build in a voice activated off switch? How did the android know how to lie, manipulate, kill?

Some fiction requires a suspension of logical and critial thinking and the watcher just has to go with the flow.  This is one of those movies. It's worth watching as a psychological thriller that just happens to be set in the future that happens to have androids. No science degree required.

The premise had me pulled in long enough for the atmosphere and tension building to do its job. The characters in this movie are interesting and multi-dimensional. There's not much I really want to put in this review because I feel like this is the kind of movie you should go into blind. Everything was done competently, the cinematography, sound, writing (sort of), acting, etc. I would give this movie a 3.5 if possible but I gave it a three because the ending stopped me from giving it a four. The first three quarters of the movie did a fantastic job of building up suspense and offering philosophical dilemmas which left me with many questions, many of which are obviously impossible to answer (duh, it's philosophy). The ending did not deliver for numerous reasons, one being a scathing plot hole of the villain making several decisions because the plot demanded it. Besides a few missteps, it was a fun film that I would absolutely recommend.

This movie has a great mood that pulls you in and then holds you through to the very end.  Solid acting--but what shines here is the plot.  This is a great drama / sci-fi / thriller.  It seems to effortlessly fade between those three genres.  Alicia Vikander is the star of the film and pulls off a thoroughly convincing act as a self-aware (and cunning) being. Both Oscar Isaac and Domhnall Gleeson are likewise convincing in their parts.  This cast of three creates a tension that acts as a catalyst for the setting--a technologically advanced house in the middle of nowhere.  The overall arc of the movie prepares you for an ending that you may not see coming.  Well done!

Amazing film.. really a mix of horror and scifi.. and a very smart sci-fi film at that, which is a refreshing change of pace from all the goofy scifi I usually see. Most of the dialogue is smart with real science behind it. The writing takes a lot of twists and turns, some of it predictable, some of it not. The visual effects are excellent considering the small budget, they clearly spent the money very effectively rather than throw it at famous celebrities and expensive locations (most of it takes place in a single setting).

As for the story, it has its flaws but overall it captivated me. Also, excellent acting from the very small but potent cast!

SPOILER: I couldn't help but wonder why he didn't program the robots with the essential "don't harm humans" rule, and also how could this genius not have a remote shut-off and control of the robots? He's too smart to have had that kind of critical oversight. But I'll give these and other flaws a pass in light of telling a powerful story.

An excellent and well thought out story to tell on film, with a few people (on screen) doing terrific work to bring it alive (and many more behind the cameras, of course). While obviously not the same story, this movie has the "spooky isolation" spirit of The Shining, but with no gore and more high tech.  In fact, Ex Machina might be just a bit more unsettling than The Shining: there are even fewer characters, it's told from a more personal POV (for myself, I identify very closely with the main character), and the premise is something non-supernatural that theoretically could actually happen (someday). The story still bothers me many days later, which is the sign of a great movie to me. 5 stars.

Generally, the story was very good. I thought the acting was mediocre, and they could have done a better job casting. The visual effects were superb. Going on a hike up the rocks was utterly pointless, and they also shot scenes in too many rooms. "Work on Character Development" instead of being consciously/sub-consciously pulled away, by needing to observe each new room. What is the significance of it? Standing in the kitchen, sitting in some half-library getting drunk, then a computer surveillance room, and a hallway, and add a bathroom brushing his teeth, walking in a huge lab, just to show a "wetware" brain, having a conversation while boxing, on and on and on.
There was absolutely no pressure, for the actors to really get to embrace just a few rooms of growing intensity. The Lead female role was done well. It also enforces the fact that she mainly stayed in her room/cell/area of confinement - just as a "Hannibal" would have to use just that area, and yet, amake it a single place that "commands attention".
I would love to see a remake in a few years. This having very few areas to shoot in, and have the characters develop in a very intense way, and the audience fully engaged by that.
My best to you all, moviegoers.

I had heard mixed opinions about this film from a few people, so decided to watch it myself.

The visuals were amazingly well done. The premise of the story is not new, so the challenge was to make a presentation that would in fact breathe a fresh wind into the concept of artificial intelligence.

Now, the problem.... close to midway into this story I was ready to walk away. It was bogged down with exposition and rather typical story elements. The exposition may have been necessary, but the characters involved were wooden to me.  This presented a lot of problems, the genius and the guinea pig, I'll call them.

Throughout the story I just found the acting to be somewhat stilted, and the scripting to be poorly paced (part of why I was ready to walk away), and also not very well written or presented. I mean we're talking about the idea of when does a machine, particularly a computer with AI cross the threshold and become self-aware? Can it become self-aware, and so be greater than the sum of it's parts - and memory (which is mostly data input by programmers)?

Science fiction writers have been covering this idea for eighty years. I would think the architects of this film would have sought out and read a whole lot of those early stories (before science caught up with the fiction), and composed a story that would have addressed the issue, one that had some depth - and which makes you think. This film's story lacked depth and didn't make me think at all. Like I said, the characters of the genius and the guinea pig were just barely more than two dimensional in content and form, walking out their roles.

Now, what about the machine. Well, if I go too deep into this thing, it will spoil everything, won't it? The machine's dialogue wasn't particularly compelling either. Some of the things it did could be viewed as interesting, had there been more thought put into the story, and the machine's role.

Suffice it to say, I am most troubled by the third act, how it played out. It really didn't seem very realistic, or plausible... to me. And there's an issue I can't discuss because it would spoil the plot. That issue concerned me. The screenwriters clearly did not deal with the dilemma at all in conceptualising that final act; they were ignorant of, or literally ignored the issue I cannot mention.

So, bottom line? Watch it for yourself. There is profanity, nudity and some disturbing stuff in the third act, so be forewarned. And if you find you want to walk out about about half way in? Don't worry about it, should you do so, you won't wish you had stayed to the end... not really.

An analyst from a Google-like corporation is chosen to test an artificial intelligence created by the company's founder in a remote location. Isolated and bound by an NDA, the analyst learns more about this new AI robot, through the Socratic method... and a friendship is created... or is it? Stylish and beautiful scenery adorns this movie and if you listen closely enough, you learn that our smart devices are opening us into a world of trouble, with the search engine companies knowing a lot more about us than we realize. Without giving anything away, I will say that the movie is not your typical Hollywood formulaic presentation. It was a good way to pass the time on a Thursday evening, in my opinion.

Although the tech aspects of this film are no longer "sci-fi" (but rather "sci-fact"), "Ex Machina" fails on many levels:

1. The film does not explain why Ava leaves Caleb "locked" in the compound.
2. The film dragged on and on for almost the entire story and was uninteresting until the last ~20 minutes.
3. There were several "who cares?!" moments throughout the film such as when Kyoko and Nathan were dancing (such a shame that Oscar Isaac was in this film).
4. The film's concept of robots killing human beings violates the Laws of Robotics: "A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm. A robot must obey orders given it by human beings except where such orders would conflict with the First Law...."

What can I say without giving too much away?  This is a movie with many twists.  Does Ava really have emotions or is she simply intelligent enough to know that it's best to pretend?  Which character is the real villain? It's like watching a cat toy with a mouse, but just when you think it's over, the mouse is able to totally exploit the cat's weakness.  If you know anything about 'Frankenstein" (the novel, not the numerous movies), you know that the Dr. Frankenstein's creature was very intelligent and complex.  It's the same with Ava.  She's created by a human who want's to determine the extent of her humanity.  If Ava has emotions, which ones does she have?  Can she control them?  This movie is a lot like modern art because different viewers may interpret the same scene differently and I don't think any interpretation can be clearly defined as "wrong."

 "Ex Machina"  was one of those cinematic lashups where  'looks are everything.  and the ONLY thing'.  As for plot,  and actors' lines,  for a parallel we find our memories being taken back to the days of  television's "Green Acres" sitcom starring one of the Gabor gals alongside Eddie Albert,  who played an attorney-turned-bumbling hobby farmer. I'm a massive science fiction nerd, and Ex Machina is easily in my Top 10 Sci-Fi movies of all time. Great performances, thought-provoking story, great acting, it's the full package.

The setup: Caleb (Domhnall Gleeson) is a programmer for a major web company, who wins a lottery resulting in an invite to the home of the company's reclusive genius CEO Nathan (Oscar Isaac). Caleb learns that Nathan is secretly building an artificial intelligence (Alicia Vikander). Slowly Nathan's sense of reality unravels as he builds rapport with the AI while suspicion mounts that Nathan may not have been entirely honest about the conditions of the trial. It's a classic sci-fi story with beautiful new effects, great production all around, excellent acting, and a rocking soundtrack.

Acting: Oscar Isaac is now a top name in Hollywood, and Ex Machina was one of the major movies that put him there. He's equal parts mysterious and intense, playing his pastiche of modern CEOs. He's threatening yet brilliant, making a perfect villain- if he is a villain. Alicia Vikander is excellent as Ava the artificial lifeform, she manages to convey the perfect sense of not-quite-human that the role calls for. Domhnall Gleeson is excellent, although his role as the everyman is less of a standout just because he makes such an excellent canvas for the audience to see themselves in the situation. Overall, everyone is great.

Production: From location shots that are absolutely breathtaking, to digital effects so good you won't even realize some of them are digital effects on first viewing, almost every frame of this movie would look gorgeous blown up to postersize and hung on your wall. Absolutely astonishingly beautiful, with excellent direction.

Music: There's been a recent trend of amazing music enhancing movies, such as Nicolas Winding Refn's movie Drive. Ex Machina makes use of a large serving of low-fi, old-school synthesizer riffs. This is a classic sci-fi story, and for fans of the genre this music will call to mind the classic era of synthesizers in '80s sci-fi films. Ex Machina has more of a modern beat that a lot of people are going to associate with chiptune but has more affinity with current trends in retro or nostalgic electronica. If the rest of the movie weren't up to snuff the music might be overblown, but it's a daring choice for a daring movie.

Overall: Sometimes a movie comes along where fans of a genre can legitimately claim that if you didn't "get it" then you might just have bad taste in movies, and this is one of those times. Ex Machina is a clever spin on an old standby of the genre, with jaw-dropping production values and an excellent soundtrack. Sometimes I re-watch the movie just to have a look at what still I might want to get blown up as a poster, and I end up not being able to choose just one (or even five, or ten). Film students especially, or anyone interested in the process, really need to dig into this one because there are layers upon layers of lessons about how to properly shoot a movie. The best part is that the vast majority of the film takes place in only a few rooms in what must be a tiny compound, so even though this is a full-fledged movie with great digital effects, it's still in the realm of relatively small-budget independent movies. An absolute tour de force in terms of direction, effects, acting... just watch it. It's important, regardless of whether or not the story "works" for you.

I thought I knew where the story was going but was pleasantly surprised.

The acting is great, the sets are done well, and I like how the cast was kept small like a play.

There are obvious comparisons to Blade Runner, which I am a longtime fan of. What this movie does with the concept is not derivative, but actually ends up being a different angle on similar subject matter.

The visual effects were also done well and made for a nice modern update.

The only negatives I can point out is some people might be lost to the pacing of the film or the lack of big action. But this isn't a big action film. This is more of an examination of human interaction.

The movie was also broken up into sections. Which made it feel like it would have been good in other forms of media. I think this would be a great read as a novel. It would possibly be even better as a video game in the vein of LA Noire.

If you like psychological sci fi, then this is probably right up your alley. A prominent corporate genius is working on his latest creation of artificial intelligence and needs a human subject to interact with it for final testing. The film starts out a little slow where a company associate is helicoptored to a remote location where he will spend a week at his boss' estate. There is substantial but necessary dialogue exchanged between the two men to build up an interesting character relationship. Once the female A.I. is introduced, the main protagonist feels an emotional connection with the android. Everything after this is psychological warfare! Who is playing who, in this test of wit? How can we determine if the emotional responses are real from the A.I or even amongst ourselves? Definitely give this one a watch; the film received an oscar nod for a reason.

The special effects in this movie are special. Instead of burying actors under CGI effects, director Alex Garland builds the effects around his actors. Consequently, you're more interested in the actors and their characters than in the effects themselves.

The movie was shot on a low-budget which might explain the abundance of indoor shots or else landscape shots of the same general area. But Garland makes his limitations in his favor. He contrasts the regimented and sterile interiors of the lab with the serene and overwhelming vistas of Nature. Nature limits the scope of Man's intelligence, but if he tries to surpass Nature, he will come to some kind of bad end.

The movie's theme is an old one going all the way back to Blade Runner and 2001, namely: the question of AI and whether or not AI droids can think and feel the same way we do. Garland doesn't answer the question because he's more interested in the emotions that develop between these four people. By the end, we humans come out behaving far worse than the synthetic humans.

My only little caveat with these AI movies is to ask, Haven't these scientists ever read Asimov's 3 Laws of Robotics? Many of the things that happen in this movie would've turned out differently had those laws been used.

Director-writer Alex Garland spins together a fascinating and tightly wound, sci-fi tale about what it means to be human and male and female. The story unravels methodically as it builds tension right up to the climax. Garland elicits stellar performances from the entire cast with Oscar Isaac a standout as Nathan Bateman, who bears more than a passing resemblance to the literary, mad geniuses of Dr. Moreau and Dr. Frankenstein. The movie's resolution also alludes to Edgar Allan Poe's classic, short story, "The Cask of Amontillado," and William Wyler's motion picture, masterpiece, The Heiress. Lastly, the music score and cinematography are the icing on the cake as they immerse the viewer into this sleek and haunting environment.

Wow. What an engaging movie! A somewhat new approach to a SciFi movie about AI's. It was very captivating. In the beginning, it was a bit slow and I was wondering about where this movie was trying to take me. However, I heard from my friends that that were would be a lot of plot twists so I stuck with it. And I'm so glad I did. The main gist of the story is that Caleb, a programmer, wins a contests to spend a week with the CEO of the company his works for, Nathan. Nathan is a recluse and a genius. He built a search engine similar to Google when he was only 17 and 94% of the world uses it. Even from the first meeting between Nathan and Caleb, there is already a hint of the darker tone that the movie will take on. But the exciting part is when Nathan finally reveals why Caleb was there, to be the human aspect of the Turing Test. He will be evaluating Ava, an AI that Nathan created. Alicia Vikander played her role beautifully. Ava's appearance is interesting in its dichotomy of a human face and human like hands versus the rest of her body which is plastic, see through, and gel like. Each interaction Caleb has with Ava is watched by Nathan except during rare instances of power failure. It is during one of these moments that Ava tells Caleb that everything is not as it seems and that Nathan has other motives. As the movie progress, there are plenty of plot twists that we didn't expect while masterfully sustaining a suspenseful and ominous tone at appropriate times. Highly recommend it others to watch.

Sci-Fi thriller from the guy who wrote the "The Beach," writer director Alex Garland brings us this story about a whiz kid computer programmer named Caleb (Domhnall Gleeson) who by winning a contest at work ends up at his reclusive genius boss's (Oscar Isaac) mansion isolated somewhere in the Nordics.  There he meets Ava, an artificial intelligence humanoid, played by the seductive Alicia Vikander with whom Caleb must use the Turing test to see if she would pass as a human.  With only these three principal actors and a high tech mansion, Garland manages to leave you feeling tense and unpredictable to the end. There are no special effects or loud soundtracks to get in the way of the dialogue between the characters, so if that is your usual sci-fi fare then maybe not the movie for you.  The performances are intimate and subtle and can be terrifying one moment to almost weirdly normal the next. For me as a sci-fi fan this movie is best thing in pure sci-fi since the movie 2001.

With a name like ex machina (I.e "deus ex machina"), I was expecting something with a little more depth.  I was hoping for an exploration of humanity, consciousness, etc..  There is some of that here to be fair, coupled with some so-so acting, building suspense and impressive CGI,

But mostly this movie is about making you feel uneasy and delivering some shock and awe via violence and unnecessary nudity.  I hate to diminish the film to that, but there was just too much skin in a story that didn't need that to say what it was trying to say.  And, for me, the story was about Ava's humanity.  Who was she?  Who could she be?  What is a creator's responsibility towards its creation? The movie hints at these questions, but never really delivers anything thought-provoking or original.  To contrast it, the Animatrix series of short films was much better at visually and narratively exploring these themes with a similar creepy undertone than this film was when it had the length of a full motion picture.

Any redeeming factors?  A few.  The suspense and sets really draw you in in a chosterphobic way.  The CGI is startling and creepy.  And the ending made me laugh... Probably more than I should have, if I'm honest.

Ex Machina presents some thought-provoking questions in a creative, entertaining way. Does the development of artificial intelligence in a "robot" mean that they should be emancipated?  Do they have the right to determine their own path?  Is dismantling such a being tantamount to murder?  Would they have the right to fight for survival, even to the extent of taking another life if necessary?  Prepare to confronted with the consequences if you guess wrong. A great movie with some real twists. The questions are answered, but what now?  The ending allows plenty of room for a sequel if they want one. Great show!

However, I have a complaint about the sound quality of the movies on Amazon streaming. For most of the movies I've watched on streaming, the dialog sound is very quiet, but the background music and effects and sounds are all incredibly loud. As a result, I spend most of the movie turning up the sound on the dialog; then dashing it down as quickly as possible so the other sounds don't break my eardrums. I would watch a lot more Amazon streaming if the sound was more balanced or, at the very least, if subtitles were added as an option on all the movies.

or, -- A Very Long Black Mirror Episode (just not in the M. Night Shamalon way.)

[Spoilers: broad plot arc points, big strokes]

Casting: Excursive dialogue fails the two male leads at times, but overall is quite good. You'll question Gleason to the end, but ultimately sells it despite some characterization gaps in the plot.
-- Oscar Isaac is credible as an insufferable Chad-Zuckerberg, but not as an Evil AI Genius AI programmer sociopath (which, it would appear, he isn't enough of at the end, to his detriment) -- the writing saves his bacon. Still better at this than as an X Wing pilot in the newest 'Star Wars' sequels. This will be the best film he ever is in.
-- Alicia Vikander is very good, exceptional given the relatively small amount she has to do/say as a robot.

Cinematography: Great contrasts, lush and verdant, to clinical and subterranean. Effects wise, no immersion issues.
Sets: Efficient and gorgeous, lends itself to themes, just right for the small cast.

Writing: In a film with this glacial a build up of tension, one has to be kept guessing right to the end. Successful apart from some weak dialogue interplay mentioned above (which at least serves the purpose of questioning just who Gleason's character is.) Vikander's character is incredibly well done, and serves to question the sincerity and reality of our own intentions and inner life at the same time as manifesting the ethical questions surrounding AI, and the reality of evil (sentient AI will be capable of choosing evil, or abstaining from self-sacrifice in an ethical double-bind.)

Every bit a film from the writer of 28 Days Later, and a great contribution to the AI/SciFi genre. Very watchable long, slow paced film that keeps you guessing, and leaves you with the right sort of questions in an open ending (more or less horrifying, depending on your own answers to them.) 7.7-8.3/10.
